The notification for the Nottingham East Labour Meeting in the sixth quarter mentioned that "we intend meetings to be inclusive and productive".
For most of my eight years as a local Labour representative in parliament, the meetings of the General Committee were exactly that.
Unfortunately today, it is no longer the tone of many of the meetings and the promise of a "kinder and kinder" policy has been long forgotten, if ever it has come true.
It has become increasingly apparent that different views are not tolerated in the Labour Party, and that each opinion is judged on whether or not it is acceptable by the leadership of the Party.
This began shortly after Jeremy took the lead, because colleagues with whom he thought he shared a similar political perspective began to expect me to take a turn and take positions with which he would never agree - whether they were on national security or on the single EU market.
Whenever I speak in public (and does not really matter what I say), there is a stream of insults on social networks that call for "depose", denouncing the policies of the centre, telling me that I must not belong to the Labour Party.
And I'm not the only one going through this.
In fact, I know that I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, since the comments I have made tend to be political.
I'm amazed at the professionalism and determination of these colleagues who face a barrage of sexist or racist insults every day, but who never back in front of them.
One of the things that disappoints me most in this era of politics is how these levels of insult have become normalized.
Jeremy Corbyn said last week that the Labour Party should promote a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we have stopped being inclusive, and with each motion of "censture" or amendment of the rules of selection the party narrows its views.
I have received numerous advice over the past two years urging me to keep my head low, not to be so expressive, and so "it would do all right" for me.
But that's not why I came to make politics.
Since I joined the Labour Party for 32 years as a student, prompted by the neglect of the Thatcher government that left the classroom of my comprehensive school literally in rubble, I sought to fight for better public services for those who most need, either as autarch or as a minister in government.
I have never hidden my policies, including in the last elections.
No one in Nottingham East could have been somewhat confused about my political positions and areas of disagreement with the current leadership.
For those who promoted the motion on Friday, all I have to say is that when the country goes to a Brexit that will harm families, businesses and our public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy on the subject of my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But indeed, the message I have is not for the Momentum of Nottingham; it is for my constituents, members of the Labour Party or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise that no threats of "depose" or political files will prevent me from acting in the sense of what I believe are the interests of all of you.
Chris Leslie is a Member of Parliament for Nottingham East
