John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
The independent schools in Scotland benefit from a curriculum of academic excellence, with this trend continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional results in the exams, reinforced by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community initiatives.
With more than 30,000 students scattered throughout Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to obtain the best level of service for both students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students to deepen their studies and access to universities, as well as to the career they have chosen and to take their place as global citizens.
Since this is an educational sector capable of designing and implementing a custom school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and sought theme in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If we talk to a man in a language he understands, we can enter his mind.
If we speak to him in his own language, we can enter his heart."
This quote reminds us that we cannot depend solely on English when we intend to create relationships and trust with people from other countries.
Based on the results of recent exams this year, we found that the languages are at the top of the table, with the highest rates of utilization of independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages reached the maximum A classification.
These data, collected at the 74 schools under the height of the SCIS, show that 72% of students obtained the maximum score of A in manderim, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that Scottish independent schools are favoring foreign languages as vital skills that will undoubtedly serve children and young people in the future.
Languages, as an option, are now viewed in the same way as STEM themes (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and not only.
A survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 concluded that, among the reasons why employers had difficulty in filling vacancies, 17% had to do with the lack of language skills.
Therefore, knowing other languages is increasingly an imperative to prepare the young generation for their future careers.
With more potential employment opportunities to demand language knowledge, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career chosen, if you have learned a second language, you will have a tangible advantage in the future with an aptitude for life like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically put a multilingual person in front of competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation, the French being the only language spoken by a two-digit ratio of 15%.
So investing now in language teaching is important for children today.
The domain of a number of languages, particularly those of developing countries, will give children the best chance to find jobs with relevance.
In Scotland, each school differs in the languages it teaches.
Some of them will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach languages considered the most important for the United Kingdom by the 2020 horizon, such as the mandarim or the Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a set of languages to choose in independent schools, supported by teaching staff specialized in the area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a pedagogical environment that prepares children and gives them the necessary skills for success, regardless of what the future holds for them.
It is undeniable that today, in a globalised business environment, languages continue to be of fundamental importance to the future of the country, so it is necessary to reflect it in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to make this option available with diversity and excellence for young Scottish people.
We have to do it.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
