Charles Czeisler, sleep medicine professor at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, was the author of the course, who believes to be the first of his type in the USA.
The inspiration for the course emerged after giving a talk about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"In the end, a girl came to me and said, "Why are you just saying this to me in the last year of the course?"
The young woman said that no one had ever mentioned the importance of sleep, which surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
The course, first taught this year, explains to students the essential concepts about how good sleep habits contribute positively to academic and athletic performance as well as to improving general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director of health services at the university, said that the institution decided to introduce the course after concluding that some students suffered severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a dormitory where students click on coffee mugs, curtains, slippers and books to be informed about the effects of caffeine and light, and how athletic performance is influenced by sleep deficiency, and the importance of a routine to collect to bed.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation may increase the risk of stroke, depression and cancer.
Then, a campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
"We know it won't change the behavior of students instantly.
However, we believe that they have the right to know, as we all have the right to know the health effects of smoking option," added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in "direct making" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students makes it a growing problem.
To ensure that we sleep sufficiently and with quality should be a "secret weapon" of students to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight loss, because sleep deprivation puts the brain in mode of hunger, constantly making them hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of physical and chemical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes last year at Harvard.
The course opened his eyes and inspired him to encourage the creation of a course for the whole campus, he said.
The next step, according to their expectations, is to ask all graduate students to attend a similar program of studies before entering the competitive institution.
