National Trust spies on the secret lives of bats
New investigations are being carried out on a property in the Scottish Highlands in order to reveal how bats use the landscape to look for food.
It is expected that the results will focus some light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help guide conservation activities in the future.
The study, carried out by scientists of the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common bats and fruit, as well as chestnuts of long ears and Daubenton bats in the Invewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations spread by the property to follow the bat activities throughout the station.
Mobile studies will also be carried out by NTS staff and volunteers with portable detectors.
The analysis by specialists of all recordings will evaluate the frequency of calls from bats and what each species is doing.
A habitat map will then be produced to create a detailed image of its behaviors on a territorial scale.
Rob Dewar, an advisor to the conservation of the nature of the NTS, expects the results to reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as grass-growing, as well as the best way to maintain forests for bats and associated species.
The population of bats in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom has declined considerably over the last century.
These animals are threatened by construction and development works that affect dormitories and make habitat scarce.
Wind turbines and lightning are also a threat, along with the flies and some chemical treatments of construction materials, as well as domestic cat attacks.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, given your night hunting habits, your ears are more useful than your eyes when it comes to catching the prey.
It is for them to use a sophisticated echo location technique to identify insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76 000 hectares of land throughout the region, takes bats very seriously.
The organization has ten trained specialists who regularly carry out studies, inspections at dorms and sometimes rescues.
It also created the first reserve in Scotland dedicated exclusively to bats, in the Thrave property in Dumfries and Galloway, which houses eight of the ten species of Scottish bats.
The director of the estate, David Thompson, says that the property is the ideal territory for them.
"Here in Thrave we have an excellent area for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, many veteran trees and all this good habitat.
However, there is still much about the bats we don't know, so the work we do here and in the other properties will help us to know more about what they need to bloom."
It highlighted the importance of checking whether there are bats before handling the properties, because the unintentional destruction of only one maternity dormitory can lead to the death of up to 400 females and young animals, which could eradicate the entire local population.
The bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill them, to sit them down, to disturb them or to destroy their dorms.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the audience to participate to help.
It was said by her: "We still have much to learn about our bats, and for many of our species, we just don't know how their populations are taking revenge."
