Information Updated on the Red Sea: Concentrations decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to new information from Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, there was a decrease in Red Sea concentrations in some areas of Tampa Bay.
FWC reported that conditions of lower proliferation of stains were identified in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
The stain of the Red Sea extends about 201 km along the coast, from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Spots can be found about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in less areas than last week.
Red Sea was also seen in Easter County.
Last week, average concentrations were recorded near or off the coast of Pinella County, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, high background concentrations in Manatee County, high or off the coast of Sarasota County, middle-to-average concentrations in Charlotte County, high-to-bottom concentrations or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
There are still reports of respiratory irritations in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
In the last week, there were no reports of respiratory irritations in the northwest of Florida.
